A functional promoter from the archaeon Halobacterium salinarum is also 
transcriptionally active in E. coli.

Liang J(#)(1), Quan Z(#)(2), Zhu J(3)(4), Gan M(5), Shen P(6).

Author information:
(1)Key laboratory of Biometallurgy, Ministry of Education, School of Minerals 
Processing and Bioengineering, Central South University, 410083, Changsha, 
China.
(2)College of Life Sciences, Wuhan University, 430000, Wuhan, China.
(3)Key laboratory of Biometallurgy, Ministry of Education, School of Minerals 
Processing and Bioengineering, Central South University, 410083, Changsha, 
China. zhujy@csu.edu.cn.
(4)College of Life Sciences, Wuhan University, 430000, Wuhan, China. 
zhujy@csu.edu.cn.
(5)Key laboratory of Biometallurgy, Ministry of Education, School of Minerals 
Processing and Bioengineering, Central South University, 410083, Changsha, 
China. ganmin0803@sina.com.
(6)College of Life Sciences, Wuhan University, 430000, Wuhan, China. 
155351273@qq.com.
(#)Contributed equally

BACKGROUND: Archaea form a third domain of life that is distinct from Bacteria 
and Eukarya. So far, many scholars have elucidated considerable details about 
the typical promoter architectures of the three domains of life. However, a 
functional promoter from the archaeon Halobacterium salinarum has never been 
studied in Escherichia coli.
RESULTS: This paper found that the promoter of Halobacterium salinarum showed a 
promoter function in Escherichia coli. This Escherichia coli promoter structure 
contains - 10 box, -10 box extension and - 29 elements, however, no -35 box. The 
- 29 element is exercised by the TATA box in archaea. And we isolated the RM10 
fragment that possessed the fusion characteristics of bacteria and archaea, 
which was overlapped with functionality of TATA box and - 29 elements.
CONCLUSIONS: The - 29 element reflects the evolutionary relationship between the 
archaeal promoter and the bacterial promoter. The result possibly indicated that 
there may be a certain internal connection between archaea and bacteria. We 
hypothesized that it provided a new viewpoint of the evolutionary relationship 
of archaea and other organisms.

