Principles and processes of comprehensive geriatric assessment (CGA) are 
increasingly being applied to subspecialties and subspecialty conditions, 
including cardiovascular patients (i.e., infective endocarditis; considerations 
of surgery or transcatheter aortic valve replacement, TAVR, for patients with 
aortic stenosis; vascular surgery) and postoperative mortality risk. In 
cardiovascular field CGA has mainly the aim to define ideal management according 
to the different typology of older adult patients (e.g., robust versus 
intermediate versus physical and cognitively disabled versus end-stage or 
dying), allowing physicians to select different therapeutic goals according to 
life expectancy; Aspect to be valued are by CGA are global health status and 
patient's decision-making capacity: CGA allows the individualized treatment 
definition and optimize the preprocedure condition.

